##NEW TYPE OF PNEUMONIA IN WUHAN: Why didn't it get more attention until today?

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

Until the Jan. 20 official report of a surge in cases of COVID-19, the streets of Wuhan looked little different. Since January 20th, the number of people wearing masks has suddenly increased. But the virus began its attack about a month ago, and it has not received much attention until today.

Reporter | Wang Shan, Zhang Congzhi, Wu Qi

South China Seafood Market: Patients on the move

▲▲▲

South China Seafood Market: Patients on the move

▲▲▲

It was a surprise for us to run into Huang Chang, a vendor at the south China Seafood Market. The market had already closed on January 1,2020. Yesterday it was three weeks since the market closed. In the evening we went to the south China seafood market with little hope of finding out more. Huang Changzheng from his has been closed out of the stall, store a lot of goods, he did not trust, so come to see. The 56-year-old, who wears a disposable mask, looks very old and in a bad mental state. He calmly told us that he was the new type of pneumonia in Wuhan, his wife Li Guifang is also, and then invited us to his home to talk.

Wuhan South China Seafood Market

Mr. and Mrs. Huang live in a community just behind the east side of the South China Seafood Market. It's almost a wall away. It's only a four-or five-minute walk home. This is an old community, the narrow side of the road filled with a variety of goods. He told us that there were many tenants who were doing business in the south China seafood market upstairs and downstairs. They were busy with their business. Although their faces were familiar, they did not have any contact with each other in private. He could not name them. As far as he knows, there are several suspected infections in that building alone.

Aren't patients supposed to be quarantined in hospitals? Why are Huang Chang and his wife still at home, and their movements are not restricted? He told us that he had just been discharged from Wuhan's No. Eleven Hospital (Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, a second-class hospital) on January 20. His admission report said he was diagnosed as having severe pneumonia (of unknown cause) , the discharge diagnosis: viral pneumonia.

A few days after he was taken to the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, his lover, Li Guifang, suffered similar symptoms: Lethargy, fever, accompanied by a mild cough and loss of appetite. She had always been in good health, but on those two days she found it impossible to take the stairs home. On January 11, she also went to the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. She told us that after the examination, the doctor told her that she had been infected, but the condition was mild and did not need to be quarantined, as long as she came every day for an intravenous drip and a nine-day course of treatment. When I saw her on the afternoon of the 21st, Li Guifang had just come back from the hospital after receiving an injection. She said she would continue to go to the hospital in the next few days.

Medical staff wearing protective clothing for treatment (photo provided by China News Service)

Isn't the patient moving freely between home and hospital a mobile source of infection? The couple had little idea of this, but Li Guifang told us that when Huang Chang was seriously ill, they lied for fear of not being admitted. Huang Chang told this newspaper that during the New Year's Day, after the south China seafood market was closed, businesses registered, and when he returned later, he did not tell the returning staff of his symptoms, nor did he say that he was taking medicine with injections. When he couldn't stand it any longer, he went to Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. Huang Chang didn't tell the doctor that he was working in the south China seafood market. He just said he lived nearby and gave him the address of the rented house. "I think if I had been working in the south China Seafood Market that day, they would not have accepted me, " said Huang, whose daughter is a nurse. Many of her classmates work in the hospital. They later heard from her, a lot of hospitals don't take patients from the seafood market. "I was lucky. I wasn't honest when I went to the hospital. "

Early symptoms: weakness

▲▲▲

Early symptoms: weakness

Huang Chang in the impression, the first symptom of the south China Seafood Market, is his next to sell fish and shrimp boss, more than 50 years old. It was mid December 2019, and she was running low on energy and then high on fever. She thought it was just a little cold, but it didn't go away after a few days, and she was taken to the hospital. Curious, Huang asked her husband, and he said, "it's pretty bad. Her lungs are infected. " At this point, no one knew she was infected with COVID-19.

Huang Changhe's ailing wife is a veteran of the south China Seafood Market. Since the construction of the market, Huang Chang has sold seafood and aquatic products here. The market, at 207 Development Avenue in Kong Hon, Wuhan, is divided into East and West by Xinhua road, a few minutes'walk from the Hankou Railway Station and passenger terminal, and is surrounded by shopping malls and office buildings. The market, where the outbreak originated, was closed on January 1st, and with the exception of patrols, the traders were rarely seen. What was once bustling was replaced by bleak and dead silence. The end of the market was the busiest time, Huang Chang has also hoarded thousands of kilograms of goods. The whole south China seafood market was originally in a festive state of preparation for the Spring Festival. More than 500 stalls in the western district where Huang Chang is located are busy with business. Nearby area county's restaurant, the market many come here to purchase goods.

Huang Chang says, after selling fish and shrimp boss Madam is in hospital, appear problem immediately is opposite a pair of husband and wife that sells dried fruit in stall mouth. It's similar to the former. He's very weak. Huang Chang looked at each other every day to get an injection, came back holding a big pot to drink water for several days, also did not get better. It wasn't until one day, when the son was selling, that he learned that the man had been delivered to the Wuhan Union Hospital. As it turned out, he had a serious lung infection and a high fever of 104.

After the New Year's Day, Huang Chang began to feel sick and tired, from downstairs to climb up the fourth floor they live more and more difficult, then began to fever, cough. After a three-day suspension at a community clinic, he remembered common cold medications, such as Cephalosporin, but the symptoms did not improve and continued to worsen. On the afternoon of January 6, Huang Changcai was sent by his family to the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital.

Even so, few knew that the virus that made them sick was later called the "COVID-19" virus. Later attempts to trace the virus to wild animals sold at the south China Seafood Market. An image circulating on the Internet shows that a stall called "popular livestock" sells as many as 42 kinds of game, including bamboo rats, dog badgers, pig badgers, fruit foxes, foxes, Koalas, peacocks, geese, etc. , "Can be slaughtered alive, frozen fresh, door-to-door delivery. ".

Net South China Seafood Market Game Price Map

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Yesterday, in the eastern part of the South China Seafood Market, we saw a shop of the same name, facing Xinhua road, very conspicuous, but has closed the shutter door. Mr. and Mrs. Huang Chang, who have been doing business in the market for more than a decade, told this magazine that there are not many stalls selling game in the south China Seafood Market, and the main ones are mainly seafood, fish and shrimp, but they do know that there are stalls selling game such as hares and snakes.

According to a study published on January 21,2020 by the Shanghai Pasteur Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and other institutions, the genome of COVID-19 in Wuhan had an average sequence similarity of ~ 70% and ~ 40% to SARS coronavirus and MERS coronavirus in 2002. The results predicted that Wuhan coronavirus has a strong ability to infect people.

His neighbor and his own illness did not attract his attention. Huang Chang thinks, the winter flu is high, everybody just got a serious cold just. By December 30,2019, a suspected Wuhan Health and Health Commission issued an "urgent notice on doing a good job in the treatment of pneumonia of unknown causes, " circulating on the Internet, it was mentioned that many cases of pneumonia of unknown cause occurred in many medical institutions in Wuhan and were related to Haixian City in south China.

On Dec. 31, the market became tense, with scores of medics in protective clothing and carrying sprayers in the early hours of the morning. On January 1, Huang Chang and others received a message that the market would be closed that day. Ironically, on that day, the Wuhan Public Security Bureau issued a circular, claiming that because some false information about "Wuhan viral pneumonia" had been circulated on the Internet, the Public Security Bureau had launched an investigation, and they had dealt with eight people according to law, for spreading false information.

Twenty days later, at a press question and answer session on the prevention and control of the "COVID-19 pneumonia epidemic" , academician Zhong Nanshan, head of the National Health Commission's high-level Expert Group, confirmed the "human-to-human" phenomenon of pneumonia in Wuhan, and had a medical infection. Earlier, on December 31,2019, the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission announced that the viral pneumonia had "not found human-to-human transmission. ".

On January 15,2020, the Wuhan Health and Health Commission released a Q & A on the prevalence of pneumonia in new coronary cases, saying that the findings showed that the viral pneumonia had not found clear evidence of human to human transmission and could not rule out the possibility of limited human to human transmission, but the risk of continuing human-to-human transmission is lower.

The hospital's tough epidemic prevention campaign

▲▲▲

The hospital's tough epidemic prevention campaign

"there was a very old patient today who was brought in by 120 and was lying on a stretcher. No one spoke to him for a long time. He was very old and lying in bed with his eyes closed, " said Li Guifang, she spent more than a week going back and forth to the hospital and saw "mostly older people, young people who looked to be in their 40s, and very few young people. " There were so many patients that the hospital added a lot of support frames for hanging bottles, filling up the entire emergency room.

From the outside, it was around January 20, when Huang Chang was discharged from hospital, that the number of new pneumonia cases in Wuhan suddenly increased. But for some doctors who have been on the front line of Wuhan's medical care, the seriousness of the situation has long been recognized. Zhang Xiaowen (not her real name) , a leading doctor at a general hospital, told scidev.net that her hospital's beds had been strained ten days ago. Since mid to late December 2019, there has been an increase in the number of patients coming to the hospital with pneumonia of unknown cause, but even as the virus has been gradually identified by the COVID-19, it has been suggested that there is an adequate supply of test kits for the virus, hospitals still don't have easy access to test kits. Doctors who had expressed concern about the outbreak through social media and other channels were interviewed. "We have isolation wards as a strong general hospital, but how can isolation wards keep up with this round of patient growth? "

Paramedics are moving the patient

Huang Chang and Li Guifang began to see a doctor in the hospital on January 6 and January 11 respectively. They saw a doctor and a nurse wearing a mask and no other protection. About two days after seeing a doctor, the medical staff at the hospital where she went put on protective clothing and goggles and were wrapped up tightly, Ms. Li said. Fever clinics and emergency departments in hospitals are also becoming more popular. January 11 that day she went to injection, from the registration to the completion of infusion only three hours, now the light registration will be a long row, calculated that a day to spend seven hours in the hospital.

Xiao Wu, 23 years old, was "recruited" on December 22,2019. Wu, a native of Huangpi, works as a salesman near the Hankou Railway Station, which is close to where he rents. He commutes to work every day by bike and has never been to a seafood market before. Xiao Wu remembers a light rain that day. He took a detour without a raincoat or umbrella. He passed the south China wholesale fruit market, just north of the south China seafood market. Two days later, Xiao Wu felt sick, began to repeatedly low-grade fever, sweating, he felt that is "the road may be caught in the rain, a cold. ".

A masked citizen rides past the south China Seafood Market.

A few days later, Xiao Wu was in the hospital for a routine blood test and liver function screening, found that there are two abnormalities, the doctor advised him to go to a large hospital. After another weekend at home, on January 1,2020, Xiao Wu arrived at the Wuhan Union Hospital. After his condition became serious, he was transferred to Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, or Wuhan Medical Treatment Center. At the Golden Pond Hospital, Xiao Wu stayed with two patients. "their situation is less severe than mine. One works as a porter at the south China Seafood Market, where the boss sells pork and ribs. The other is an elderly aunt in her 50s who lives near the market. But it turned out to be a cold and she was discharged in about five days and then quickly moved on to someone else."

Because of the increase in patients, Wu told the Financial Times that on Jan. 10, his hospital divided patients into two categories: those with mild symptoms and those with severe symptoms in one room. Wu lives with three other patients. "I was in pretty good shape by then, and the three of them were basically on oxygen all day, and they were in pretty bad shape. "

Fei Qing (not his real name) , a doctor in charge of a top-three hospital in Wuhan, said the situation would have been much better if he had faced the real situation more than 10 days ago and been prepared for the outbreak. Now his hospital is struggling to accept new patients, because the existing patients have made the hospital in overdrive, the number of health care workers infected is not small.

Passengers wearing face masks wait for a train at the Waiting Hall of Wuhan Railway Station on Jan. 21. (photo provided by China News Service)

On January 21,2020, the Wuhan COVID-19 pneumonia epidemic prevention and Control Headquarters held a press conference on the same day to address the issue of bed tension. Peng Houpeng, vice director of Wuhan's Health Commission, said at the meeting that Wuhan has arranged for 800 beds in three designated hospitals to receive and treat patients, and 1,200 beds will be vacated in the shortest time. All confirmed patients will enjoy free medical treatment.

On January 22, the State Council Information Office held a news conference in the morning, and Li Bin, Deputy Director of the National Health Commission, said that as of 2400 hours on January 21, a total of 440 cases of COVID-19 infection and 9 deaths have been reported in 13 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities. Three new deaths were reported, all in Hubei Province.

(Huang Chang, Xiao Wu, Li Guifang are all pseudonyms)
